# Git Workflow

## Branching
- `main` — production-ready code only. Never commit directly to main.
- Branch per feature/fix: `feature/<short-description>`, `fix/<short-description>`
- Branch from `main`, merge back to `main` via PR.
- Keep branches short-lived — one logical piece of work per branch.

## Commits — small and focused
- **One logical change per commit.** A commit should do exactly one thing.
- Never bundle unrelated changes (e.g. a bug fix + a refactor + a new feature in one commit).
- Commit frequently — after each passing test, after each module is complete.
- A good rule of thumb: if you can't summarise the commit in ~50 characters, it's too big.

## Commit message format (Conventional Commits)
```
<type>(<scope>): <short summary>

[optional body — why, not what]
```

**Types:**
| Type | Use for |
|------|---------|
| `feat` | New feature or module |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |
| `refactor` | Restructuring without behaviour change |
| `chore` | Config, tooling, deps, CI |
| `docs` | Documentation only |

**Examples:**
```
feat(db): add runs and visits query helpers
test(config): add env validation edge case tests
fix(db): order runs by id desc to handle same-millisecond inserts
chore: add down() migrations for knex rollback support
```

## When to commit (during development)
Following the TDD workflow in `.ai/todo.md`:
- After tests are written and failing → `test(<scope>): add <module> tests`
- After implementation makes tests pass → `feat(<scope>): implement <module>`
- After a bug is caught and fixed → `fix(<scope>): <what was wrong>`

## Pull Requests
- One PR per feature branch.
- PR title follows the same Conventional Commits format.
- Link PR to the relevant todo item in `.ai/todo.md`.
- Squash-merge to keep main history clean.
